Why doesn't the Fed do its job?
STANFORD – The nomination of new board members at the US central bank Federal Reserve gives the people in America – and the US Congress – the opportunity to think about the world's most important central bank and its future path.
The obvious first question is how it was possible that the Fed failed its most important mandate – ensuring price stability – so badly.
That the Fed was completely surprised by current inflation suggests a fundamental failure.
Now, undoubtedly, institutional soul-searching is in order.
Doch while monetary policy makes headlines, the Fed is now mainly significant as a financial regulator.
Another big question therefore is whether it will use its enormous power to push forward climate or social policy.
The Fed could, for example, deny companies in the field of fossil energy credit, it could require banks to only grant credits to companies with certified net-zero-emissions plans, or direct the credit granting towards desired alternatives.
Moreover, it could decide to take its regulatory activities explicitly in the name of equality or ethnic justice, by instructing banks to prescribe where and to whom credits are granted, who is hired and who is fired, and so on.
But before we turn to the question of which direction the Fed's regulation will or should move, we first need to clarify the Fed's serious failure.
In the year 2008, the US government made a fateful decision: financial institutions could still obtain the money for risky investments primarily through the sale of short-term, run-anfälligen debt titles, but hordes of new regulatory agencies would then evaluate the risk potential of the institutions' assets.
The hope was that the regulatory authorities would no longer overlook large sums of money in the form of subprime mortgage loans in the bank balance sheets.
However, in the following ten years of more detailed regulation and regular scenario-based „stress tests, " the Fed's regulatory army never once asked themselves what would actually happen in the event of a pandemic.
When the pandemic actually entered in the early 2020, the Fed discarded their „never again“ promises from 2008 and intervened on a larger scale.
In March, commercial banks proved unable to act as intermediaries on the market for ordinary US government bonds.
Therefore the Fed supported the market.
Critics had long pointed out the problems with the Fed's liquidity rules. The corrections on the markets would have been simple, but the obvious reforms were pushed onto the long chair.
Later it came to a run on money market funds.
The Fed saved the money market funds again.
Nothing is easier to fix than a run on the money market, but it never came to that.
Moreover, the Fed also financed the issuance of new municipal bonds and supported the prices of corporate bonds, by essentially providing a guarantee with the motto "Whatever it takes".
In 2008, the Fed and the US Treasury Department opposed the idea of raising the market price of all mortgages within the framework of the financial industry bailout - the Troubled Assets Relief Program.
However, in 2020, they introduced a specific lower bound for corporate bond prices with the "Powell put".
The predictable response to this criticism will be: So what?
The lockdowns due to Covid-19 could have certainly triggered a financial crisis.
The flood of rescue measures has worked so well that our problem today is inflation.
We need not worry about systemic risks, as the Fed and the US Treasury will simply put out every new fire with a new flood of money.
The problem lies, of course, in the incentives that these strategies have created.
Why bother using real money or balance sheet space for purchases at falling prices, providing liquidity, or treating a "forced sale" as a "buying opportunity"?
The Fed will naturally overrule everything and pocket the profits.
Why as a company still issue stocks when you can simply take a loan knowing that the state will support the debt or help the company out of trouble, like it was the case with airlines?
Why as an investor hesitate when it comes to buying dubious papers when their value is guaranteed in bad times by another "Whatever-it-takes" promise from the Fed?
No wonder America is drowning in debt.
Everyone assumes that the taxpayers will bear the losses in the next downturn.
Student loans, government pensions, and mortgages are piling up and waiting for Uncle Sam's rescue action to come along.
Yet every new crisis requires even more extensive transfusions.
Bondholders will eventually refuse to invest more money in rescue efforts and people will not be thrilled with trillions of new printed money.
If the rescue packages expected by all do not materialize, we will wake up in a huge fire – and the fire station will have been burned down.
In the year 2008, regulatory authorities and lawmakers at least recognized the moral risk and were concerned that in good times investors would reap profits while in bad times taxpayers would bear the losses.
In 2020, however, one was only overcome with self-satisfaction with the rescue efforts.
Exactly the Fed, which in 2008 did not see the risks of subprime mortgages, just as it did not see the pandemic in 2020 and will now conduct stress tests in view of "climate risks," will undoubtedly also overlook the next war, the next pandemic, the next state bankruptcy or another disruptive event.
The Fed's regulators do not even ask themselves questions about the mentioned events.
And although word salads are produced about "interconnections", "strategic interactions", "network effects", and "credit cycles", they have not been able to define the "systemic" risk at all, apart from it becoming a catch-all term that grants regulatory authorities all-encompassing power.
Regulatory authorities will never be able to predict risks, measure the assets of financial institutions precisely, or ensure that immense debts are always repaid.
We must reverse the fundamental premise of a financial system in which the state always stands by for debt mountains in bad times. And we must do it before the fire department is put to the test.
A better regulation can bridge partisan trenches.
The Left is right when it says that the big banks are inefficient oligopolies that benefit most Americans little.
However, it starts from the wrong cause.
A massive effort to comply with regulations is a major obstacle to market entry.
The call for "more" regulation is pointless.
Regulations are either smart or dumb, effective or ineffective, full of unwanted consequences or well-conceived.
We need better regulation.
We need more capital, not thousands of pages of rules.
Capital provides a buffer against all shocks and does not require regulatory authorities to possess clairvoyant abilities.
The Fed scandalously shut down companies in the narrow banking sector and payment service providers that could contribute to meeting the financial needs of many people in America.
Before it commits itself to saving the planet and making amends for injustices, the Fed should be held accountable for how poorly it performs its fundamental task of protecting the financial system.
